#1 Colon carcinoma (T4, N2b, M0) stage IIIC
I reviewed these findings with Mr. Ralston and his sister.  We went over his current clinical findings as well as surgical results.  His post-op scans are without evidence of recurrence and the pulmonary nodule is also unchanged.  His CEA has normalized, and he is feeling much better following drainage of the fluid collection.  I did review the case with his surgeon, Dr. Stein.  I asked about the path report showing a nest of cells in a retroperitoneal biopsy.  Dr. Stein states that this specimen was taken out quite early in the course the surgery.  This was not something that was taken out at the end of en bloc resection.  This was reviewed again with the patient.
We discussed pathology and the fact that he has extensive nodal involvement.  Rish of recurrence is quite high but we would hope that he would benefit from FOLFOX chemotherapy.  I reviewed use of monoclonal antibody in this setting.  Unfortunately we do not have proof that patients will benefit from additional bevacizumab or cetuximab, therefore, I have recommended use of FOLFOX.  We went over logistics as well as side-effects.  We reviewed the neuropathy side-effects associated with oxaliplatin.  One needs to monitor for more significant, persistent neuropathy toward the end of his six-month course.  If indeed he is having more persistent neuropathy, one may wish to eliminate the oxaliplatin after eight, nine, or ten cycles.
We also talked about further follow-up.  Dr. Stein was concerned about the risk of recurrence and was suggesting more frequent scans.  This could be considered half-way through his adjuvant therapy and then at the end of his adjuvant therapy.  Routine follow-up quarter every three to six-months can be done after completion of treatment.  We went over potential sites of recurrence as well as natural history of recurrent disease.  He is aware of possible treatment options in the future and is hoping for continued benefit from the treatments.  I would be happy to see him in the future should he wish to return here for routine follow-up.  His sister can be in touch with us, and we will contact Dr. Hammitt regarding our final recommendations.
ADVANCE DIRECTIVES
Advance directive or living will: No, not interested in additional information.
PATIENT EDUCATION
Ready to learn, no apparent learning barriers were identified; learning preferences include listening.  Explained diagnosis and treatment plan; patient expressed understanding of the content.

