[start section id="20103"]

#1 Resected locally advanced colon carcinoma.
ONCOLOGIC HISTORY
1.  April 2010 - he presented at a general medical exam complaining of bright-red blood over the last five to six-months and also had anemia.
2.  April 20, 2010 - colonoscopy found a circumferential mass at the hepatic flexure.
3.  April 22, 2010 - referred to MetroWest County Hospital Clinic.  CT-scan showed a large right-sided colon mass and an indeterminate 4-mm nodule near the major fissure in the lung.  No evidence though of definitive distant metastasis.  CEA was 5.4.
4.  April 23, 2010 - colonoscopy was repeated, again identifying the hepatic flexure mass.  This was biopsied and found to be grade 4 (of 4) adenocarcinoma with signet ring cell features.  HNPCC testing was negative.  Also noted were other polyps.
5.  April 27, 2010 - taken by Dr. Stein for resection of the hepatic flexure mass.  There was direct invasion into the duodenum and segment VII of the liver, as well as the pylorus.  Pathology showed a poorly-differentiated adenocarcinoma with signet ring cell features and possible neuroendocrine features involving 15 of 22 lymph nodes (T4N2M0, Stage IIIc).
Post-op the patient did have complications with fever and abscess formation.  He was hospitalized locally.  He was put on antibiotics and had a drain placed.  Drain was removed and his symptoms have recovered.  Today he had left chest Port-A-Cath placed.  His bowels back to normal.  He still has been having some abdominal pain-related surgical site.  This is improving.

[end section id="20103"]

